<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1927-04-08T07:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1927-04-08T07:00:00-05:00" n="85" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d85">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.00/8625: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in China</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">MacMurray</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><seg rendition="#center">[Paraphrase]</seg></opener>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Peking</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1927-04-08T20:00:00+08:00"><hi rend="italic">April 8,
                                        1927—8 p.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received April 8—6:25
                                p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>388. My No. 359, April 6, 10 a.m.</p>
                        <list>
                            <label>1.</label>
                            <item>Foreign commandants at conference, Tientsin, April 6, unanimously
                                expressed the opinion that the more troops on the spot the less
                                likely the necessity will be to take military action and they
                                submitted that to this end an increase of the garrisons in North
                                China to 25,000 men forthwith would be the best solution. They
                                agreed to transmit this opinion to their respective
                                Ministers.</item>
                            <label>2.</label>
                            <item>I concur.</item>
                        </list>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">MacMurray</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
